  "local_port": 49894,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some of the best stories about Virender Sehwag?",
  "response": "Virender Sehwag, known for his explosive batting and fearless approach, has numerous legendary stories associated with his cricketing career. Here are some of the most memorable ones:\n\n### 1. **The Triple Century on 278 Balls (2004)**\n   - Sehwag became the first Indian to score a triple century in Test cricket against Pakistan in Multan. He achieved this feat in just 278 balls, showcasing his aggressive style. The innings included 39 fours and 6 sixes, and it remains one of the most iconic innings in Indian cricket history.\n\n### 2. **The 201* Against Sri Lanka (2009)**\n   - In a Test match against Sri Lanka, Sehwag scored an unbeaten 201* on the first day itself. This was one of the fastest double centuries in Test cricket, and it came at a staggering strike rate of over 85. His ability to dominate bowlers from the outset was on full display.\n\n### 3. **The 319 Against South Africa (2008)**\n   - Sehwag scored his second triple century in Test cricket, becoming the first Indian to do so. This innings came against South Africa in Chennai, and he reached the milestone in just 278 balls, matching his previous triple century in terms of speed.\n\n### 4. **The ODI Double Century (2011)**\n   - Sehwag was on the verge of breaking the record for the highest individual score in ODIs when he scored 219 against West Indies. Although he missed Sachin Tendulkar's then-record by just 10 runs, his innings was a masterclass in aggressive batting.\n\n### 5. **The \"See the Ball, Hit the Ball\" Philosophy**\n   - Sehwag\u2019s batting philosophy was simple yet effective: \"See the ball, hit the ball.\" He rarely bothered about the bowler's reputation or the match situation. This approach often left bowlers and spectators in awe, as he would dispatch even good deliveries to the boundary.\n\n### 6. **The Lunchtime Declaration (2004)**\n   - During his triple century in Multan, then-captain Rahul Dravid declared the innings at lunch when Sehwag was batting on 309. Sehwag, unaware of the declaration, was ready to bat after lunch and was surprised when he learned that the innings had been declared. However, he took it in good spirit, showcasing his team-first attitude.\n\n### 7. **The Quickfire 293 Against Sri Lanka (2009)**\n   - In a Test match against Sri Lanka, Sehwag scored 293 at a strike rate of over 90, the highest score by an Indian batsman who was dismissed just short of a triple century. His innings included 40 fours and 7 sixes, and it was a testament to his ability to score quickly even in the longest format of the game.\n\n### 8. **The 2010 T20 World Cup Semi-Final**\n   - In the semi-final of the 2010 T20 World Cup against Pakistan, Sehwag played a crucial knock of 38 off just 25 balls, which helped India set a competitive total. His partnership with Gautam Gambhir laid the foundation for India\u2019s victory, although they eventually lost the final to England.\n\n### 9. **The \"Nervous 90s\" Joke**\n   - Sehwag was known for his disdain for the \"nervous 90s.\" He often joked that he didn\u2019t feel any pressure in the 90s because he would either get out or get to a century quickly. His ability to score centuries at a rapid pace was a testament to his confidence and skill.\n\n### 10. **The Last Ball Six (2008)**\n   - In a Test match against England, Sehwag hit a six off the last ball of the day to reach his century. This audacious move was typical of Sehwag, who never shied away from taking risks, even in Test cricket.\n\n### 11. **The 122* Against England (2008)**\n   - In a Test match against England, Sehwag scored an unbeaten 122 in the fourth innings to guide India to a comfortable chase. His innings was crucial in ensuring that India didn\u2019t lose the match, and it showcased his ability to adapt to different situations.\n\n### 12. **The Farewell Match (2013)**\n   - Sehwag\u2019s last international match was a T20 game against Pakistan in 2013. Although he didn\u2019t make a significant contribution with the bat, his presence was felt, and fans gave him a standing ovation as he walked off the field for the last time.\n\nSehwag\u2019s career is filled with such stories that highlight his extraordinary talent, audacity, and impact on the game. His ability to change the course of a match single-handedly made him one of the most exciting cricketers to watch.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
